---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHero from '../../components/PageHero.astro';

// The ActionKind list below is the FULL closed enum from pkg/ai/types.go
// (OSS). Regenerate against that file when a release adds a kind.
const actionKinds = [
  { kind: 'DeletePod', line: 'Delete a single Pod so its controller reschedules it — the restart-class remediation.' },
  { kind: 'DeleteJob', line: 'Delete a stuck or failed Job so its owner (CronJob / operator) can recreate it.' },
  { kind: 'PatchDeployment', line: 'Patch a Deployment — every JSONPath in the patch must pass the patch validator allowlist (no image, no replica changes).' },
  { kind: 'DeleteCertRequest', line: 'Delete a stuck cert-manager CertificateRequest so issuance retries.' },
  { kind: 'DeleteACMEOrder', line: 'Delete a stuck ACME Order so the challenge re-runs.' },
  { kind: 'ApplyManifest', line: 'Apply a full manifest (v1.15) — constrained by ValidateManifest before it can ever reach an approval link.' },
  { kind: 'ProposePullRequest', line: 'No direct cluster mutation (v1.17) — the GitOps path: CHA opens a pull request against your repo and the merge is the approval.' },
];

const layers = [
  {
    name: 'Action-kind allowlist',
    summary:
      'The agent can only propose action_kinds from a closed enum compiled into pkg/ai — anything outside it is rejected by the validator before the proposal even reaches an operator. The full list today:',
    items: actionKinds,
    where: 'pkg/ai/types.go — ActionKind closed enum',
  },
  {
    name: 'Target-resource scope',
    summary:
      "Each action_kind ships with a hard-coded target-resource filter. DeletePod only matches Pod resources. PatchDeployment payloads are gated JSONPath-by-JSONPath by the patch validator — not container images, not replicas. ApplyManifest payloads must pass ValidateManifest.",
    where: 'ai/approval/patch_validator.go — allow-list of JSONPaths',
  },
  {
    name: 'Namespace protection',
    summary:
      'Protected namespaces are a compiled-in floor (kube-system, kube-public, kube-node-lease, rook-ceph, vault, external-secrets, cnpg-system) the agent refuses to touch. Operators extend the list append-only — CHA_PROTECTED_NAMESPACES_EXTRA, rendered from Helm protectedNamespaces.extra or the operator CR — so nothing can ever remove a compiled-in namespace. The fixer guard and the AI validator consume the same set, and the detect side escalates (not shields) findings in protected namespaces.',
    where: 'pkg/ai/protected.go — append-only extras over the validate.go floor',
  },
  {
    name: 'GitOps-managed skip',
    summary:
      "Resources labelled by Argo CD, Flux, or Helm (app.kubernetes.io/managed-by, argocd.argoproj.io/instance, helm.sh/release) are skipped — the agent doesn't fight a reconciliation loop.",
    where: 'internal/fix/gitops.go — GitOpsReason()',
  },
  {
    name: 'Signed JWT click-to-fix',
    summary:
      "Every T1+ mutation is wrapped in an Ed25519-signed JWT URL delivered to the operator via Slack or ticket. The approval-server verifies signature + expiry + JTI (one-time use). T2 plan steps additionally enforce prerequisite ordering at execution time — a step cannot run before its predecessor has executed. Without the click, nothing mutates — unless you explicitly enable confidence-gated auto-merge (off by default; Wilson lower bound ≥0.95; the PR body is re-fetched from the forge and its Ed25519 attestation re-verified and field-bound before merge; every safety gate must pass).",
    where: 'ai/approval/{signer,verifier,replay}.go',
  },
  {
    name: 'Dual-approval for T3',
    summary:
      "Vault break-glass runbooks (T3) require two distinct approvers separated by at least 30 minutes. The runbook itself is never executed by CHA — the operator runs it manually after dual approval. Key names only, never values; ${VALUE_*} placeholders in command templates.",
    where: 'ai/approval/runbook_store.go — RecordApproval',
  },
  {
    name: 'Hash-chained audit',
    summary:
      "Every AI action (LLM call, proposal created, validator decision, approval granted, action applied, post-apply verify) emits an AuditEvent with prev_hash chained against the prior event. Tamper-evident even if a downstream sink is compromised. The hash chain itself is Apache-2.0 OSS; the streaming sinks (JSONL, Loki, OTLP) ship in the paid binary.",
    where: 'pkg/audit/hash_chain.go (OSS)',
  },
  {
    name: 'Per-(approver, class) rate budget',
    summary:
      'Approval executions are token-bucket budgeted per (approver, action class) pair — default 10 executions per hour per pair, per-class overrides supported, and the bucket key is collision-safe so a crafted approver/class pair cannot alias another pair\'s budget. Layer-2 LLM investigations draw on their own budget. Prevents both flapping-workload cost blowup and a single approver bulk-approving a class of actions.',
    where: 'ai/rate_limit.go — TakeApproval (enforced in the approval-server)',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CHA &mdash; Action policy (the leash on the agent)"
  description="The agent has reasoning power; the policy has the leash. Operator-defined action_kinds, target-namespace allowlists, GitOps-managed skip, signed JWT click-to-fix URLs, dual-approval for T3, hash-chained audit. Every layer is in the Apache-2.0 source."
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Features &middot; Action policy"
    title="The agent reasons. The policy decides what it can touch."
    subtitle="Every layer of CHA's safety envelope is operator-defined and in code you can read before you install. Eight layers; here's all of them."
  />

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-20">
    <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-700 dark:text-zinc-300">
        Komodor, Robusta, Causely, NeuBird &mdash; they observe and suggest.
        CHA mutates. That changes the safety story. An agent that can actually
        change cluster state needs a policy that says <em>which</em> changes
        are allowed, <em>where</em>, and under <em>which approval</em>. Eight
        layers, all in code you can read before you install.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 space-y-5">
      {layers.map((l, i) => (
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200/80 bg-white p-7 shadow-sm dark:border-zinc-800/80 dark:bg-zinc-900/60">
          <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-50">
              {i + 1}. {l.name}
            </h3>
            <code class="ml-4 text-xs font-mono text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-500">
              {l.where}
            </code>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            {l.summary}
          </p>
          {l.items && (
            <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
              {l.items.map((k) => (
                <li>
                  <code class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-100">{k.kind}</code>
                  <span class="ml-2">{k.line}</span>
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          )}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 rounded-2xl border border-zinc-200/80 bg-zinc-50/60 p-8 dark:border-zinc-800/80 dark:bg-zinc-950/40">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-50">
        Why this matters for an AI SRE.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        An LLM-powered agent without policy is a liability &mdash; reasoning
        capability without a brake. CHA's design says the LLM can propose
        anything, but only operator-allowlisted action_kinds against
        operator-allowlisted namespaces can ever be executed, and only
        after a signed-JWT operator click (dual-approval for break-glass).
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        That makes CHA suitable for the kinds of deployments where pure-LLM
        autonomy is a non-starter: regulated industries, sovereign clouds,
        air-gapped clusters, FedRAMP track. The agent gets to be smart; the
        policy decides what smart looks like in your environment.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        <a
          href="/security/"
          class="font-medium text-accent-600 hover:text-accent-700 dark:text-accent-400 dark:hover:text-accent-300"
        >
          Read the full security posture &rarr;
        </a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
